author: @alansmithee419
text:
Wait a minute. Derlord didn't just set two traps to see if the chunk would spawn in (which would merely show the entity exists).
He set a trap to find out if whatever was following him could read his chat messages, and if it was intelligent.
He tells us about the hopper, thereby telling the entity and allowing it to nullify that trap.
He doesn't tell us about the dirt block, hiding it from the entity as well - it nullifies the hopper but doesn't nullify this simpler trap, because it was too distracted by the "clever" trap Derlord "hid" to notice this much simpler one that was out in the open.

Derlord discovered it was intelligent *by outsmarting it.*
That's a f***ing incredible move.

post_title: Stranger Things in Brawl Talk!
author: @alvi7vivageek
text:
While looking at all the Brawl Stars skins to suggest which ones could become bosses in the Track Hawkins mode when that mode becomes permanent in the game, I came across the "Chaos Gang" theme, which has exactly 3 brawlers: Skull Crow, Outlaw Lola, and Bandit Poco.
This gave me an idea: what if, in some seasons or difficulty levels, the Track Hawkins mode had a Boss Trio instead of just 1 Brawler boss?

In this example, players start by facing one of the 3 brawlers from the Chaos Gang theme in the first difficulties, and after facing each Brawler alone in the first 3 difficulties (Normal, Hard, Veteran), the player will face a duo of this Gang in Master mode and the complete Chaos Gang in Insane mode.

Other themes that only have 3 Brawlers with skins can be used in the same way to create Boss Trios for the Track Hawkins mode.

post_title: THE BIG FINALE (Dispatch 7 & 8)
author: @wxzjet
text:
on the topic of Invisigal smoking not being good for her lungs: I think that, plus her asthma, is a representation of her self-destructive tendencies and penchant for running from problems rather than facing them.
Her ability is reliant on her ability to hold her breath, but she has asthma, so she's already nerfed in that category. Instead of facing this problem and working to better it, she instead makes it even worse by smoking, and thus refuses to actually tackle her problems, and instead hides from and ignores them. The ironic thing is that she uses her invisibility to run and hide, so the more she fucks up her lungs (runs from her problems), the worse she'll be at using her power (being able to hide from her problems).
This is the same as what she does all throughout the game: when she has a problem, she just runs and hides or quits, and she's actively struggling to break this habit during the story

author: @silentverdict
text: The HDMI limits are because of limitations of AMD's  Linux drivers. The Group that governs HDMI spec didn't want to opensource HDMI 2.1 which AMD required because their linux drivers are OSS. I discovered that when trying to run my 4k 240hz monitor on my new linux box and ended up swapping to DP. That's why you can get the benefits of HDMI 2.1's higher bandwidth, but not the unique things that HDMI 2.1 can do with DSC.

post_title: The (Somewhat) Complete Lore of Silksong
author: @SugarBombChar
text:
Motherhood is a large theme in this game.

Shakra's storyline, we find out, leads to her mother who she respected more as a master; Hornet's memory of her mother being both tragic and beautiful - her advice being to seek her own path while Hornet not being able to really recall her face; Grandmother Silk's love for Lace meanwhile her neglect of Phantom; Huntress's side quest; Hornet confronting the White Lady in her memory - not the Pale King; Many of the Journal Entries; Even the first boss you fight is the Moss Mother. What to conclude from that, I have no idea.

post_title: Hunting a Minecraft Player Who Shouldn't Exist
author: @Spookileoz
text:
Ok so after watching the whole vid, i can conclude that parrot is actually taking the exact path wifies took. Both of them taught they were doing it for the better good and were blinded by their respective objectives, wifies being protecting innocent parrot and parrot being protecting innocent players. Both of them went thru different stages of this "villain" process. First, they actually were just harmlessly chasing their objective, as a "hero", with actual wifies helping parrot and parrot helping players. Then, the middle ground, where they are slowly becoming the "villain", with bits of realisation (for example when wifies abbandoned parrot and burned the compass at the farlands vid, but later realised what he did and came back, or parrot right now revealing wemmbus identity, but then thinking if it was right or wrong). And then, they just become the "villain" with "the director" becoming this egocentric character that is blinded by his obsession of protecting parrot, which he ll do by all means, good and bad. I think the same could happen to parrot some day, maybe justified by the trauma he revevied thruought yhe whole mafia lore. This would also lowkey add up to what ash said, that parrot/spoke would become the very thing they sweared to destroy, without even realising it. This may be a stretch but it would actually make sense and would be an amazing end to the whole lore, with parrot using his intelligence to destroy the server.
Hopefully that doesnt happen tho, and i lowkey wanna see what examples he uses to show the final stage or how the series will go on now. Maybe parrot actually doesnt do the same mistake as wifies and slowly comes to a "realisation", who knows.

post_title: IT ALL ENDS HERE - Dispatch (Ep. 7 + 8)
author: @BFWandz
text:
So here's how all the endings are:

Every ending you succeed in taking down Shroud and his team.
Every ending beef survives.
If you romanced someone, you will kiss your romantic choice at the end:
If you romanced Invisigal, you will kiss her on a stretcher. If you romanced Blonde Blazer, you will kiss her on a car. If you didn‚Äôt romance either of them, you will get the achievement ‚ÄúKept romance out of the workplace‚Äù.
If you leaned in for the kiss from Invisgal in the locker room, it changes the romantic interest, even if you went on a date with Blonde Blazer. In the end you will get the "complicated" achievement.

If you managed to save the city from coupe/sonar, you will be given the choice to forgive/forget them after the fight. If you didn‚Äôt manage to save the city, coupe/sonar will automatically go to prison.

If you choose to give shroud both the prototype and the astral pulse, he will put the prototype in his head. If you give him the prototype/astral pulse, either way he ends up with the astral pulse in his head. 
Either
IF you didn‚Äôt build a relationship with invisigal
A: Invisigal will show up and kill shroud before you get the chance to spare/kill him. She takes his mask, insinuating she will become the next big villain. She will not be on a stretcher afterwards.

IF you built a relationship with invisigal:
B: You kill shroud, you are suspended from the Z team pending investigation, but everyone still congratulates you and is happy for you.

OR

C: You spare shroud, there‚Äôs no comment about being suspended, and everyone is still happy and congratulates you.

Sorry for the long message. I had to play this game a few times. And in case anyone was curious

post_title: Hermitcraft 11: Episode 2 - Trying New Things
author: @_Leninade
text:
I was thinking this in the last video, and this one's confirmed it: I think Mumbo's actually mastered the minecraft video. Like, the Hermits and others are fantastic at different things - great builders, entertainers, etc - but I don't think anyone quite holds a candle to the tightness of Mumbo's editing, the way he creates subtle narratives, the layers of little jokes, the self-aware, sort of Brechtian (if I can be that pretentious) references to the medium, even the continuity of the style with the font, cards, etc. It all comes together to create something without fault. This isn't to disparage anyone else - all the Hermits are obviously excellent at what they do - but Mumbo's videos have reached the point now of being more well-thought-out and having more attention to detail in them than many TV shows I've seen, with thousands of times the budget and hundreds of people working on them.

I started watching early in Season 2 (coming from Monkeyfarm's channel), and the videos back then were great - Mumbo's always been a skilled entertainer - but it's incredible how far things have grown. In the time that Minecraft videos have turned from hobbyists' passion projects into a full-fledged industry, Mumbo's videos have somehow managed to both outpace the professionalism of most others and maintain an earnestness that's become increagingly rare.

I'm sorry if this reads as fawning or anything, I just find it pretty inspiring.

post_title: No, I Am Not Human
author: @crowthebeloved4266
text:
Fun? fact. At 5:50 ballerinas are dancing on the tv, and the protag/narrator says while the dance is elegant, it evokes anxious thoughts. It could be a reference to how back in 1980's, the soviet media would play Swan Lake over and over on broadcasts after multiple deaths of leaders had just occurred, to mask uncertainty and chaos about the news so nobody would freak out. Though in the end it just reversed itself, and now is associated with political turmoil and crisis after the incident.

No clue if its an actual reference or just a total coincidence, but its a cool detail if so!

post_title: Pirate Software: The Legacy of a Liar
author: @kochiyama
text: The funniest thing for me is the voice. I think this is just because I'm an old Howard Stern listener, but it's incredibly obvious to me the sort of processing he uses on his voice to make it sound like that. It's exactly what Howard Stern has done for decades, and it has an extremely distinctive sound to it. The difference is, Howard Stern is totally open about it, he says "yeah, I have the engineers crank the compression up on my mic really high, it evens out my voice and makes it sound deeper and more resonant, I like the way it sounds." Meanwhile, Thor has to make up all these goofy stories about going through "second puberty" or whatever, It's embarrassing and it reeks of insecurity.

post_title: What's On The Edge Of Skyrim?
author: @Tomniverse
text: The day before Skyrim was first released, I launched up oblivion and put my ~400 hour character at the northern edge of the map looking north, and then saved and quit the game. So he would be watching over my entire Skyrim play through.

post_title: What's On The Edge Of Skyrim?
author: @grady3251
text: As someone who has played an ungodly amount of Skyrim, and was instantly familiar with several of these locations, there's something surreal about watching a video where someone else talks about them. Like these locations wouldnt show up in a playthrough series or a video about lore. They're places that are almost exclusive to your own experience of the game. But, of course, this is Any Austin.

post_title: What's On The Edge Of Skyrim?
author: @andydepissant
text:
One of my most vivid memories in gaming is noticing the newspapers blowing around in GTA 3, walking to them and realising you couldn't make the camera look all the way down. So we looked around for ages to get a sniper rifle. Then we came back to the spot, waited for newspapers again. Finally saw one, ran over and sighted it through the sniper rifle and there you go... You can read the newspaper! 

I think that's the feeling Austin is talking about here: The tingle of a hint of a feeling you could disappear inside the game.
